.\" Modified for the cute-alden fork on 2026-04-21.
.\" See the repository README.md and CHANGELOG for downstream changes.
.TH CUTE-ALDEN 1 "@release_date@" "@PACKAGE_STRING@" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
@PACKAGE@ \- detachable terminal sessions without breaking scrollback
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B @PACKAGE@
.RI [ OPTIONS .\|.\|.\|]
.RB [ \-\-
.IR "SHELL " [ SHELLOPTS .\|.\|.\|]]
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
The
.B @PACKAGE@
program allows a long-running terminal-based process to survive when the
user's connection disappears, and allows the user to subsequently reconnect
to the surviving process.  Unlike other systems that serve a similar
purpose,
.B @PACKAGE@
passes the connection transparently.  It is not a terminal emulator
itself, and it does not interfere with, nor attempt to replace,
the scrollback features built into GUI terminal emulators.
.PP
A user who freshly invokes
.B @PACKAGE@
at the command line will be presented with the command prompt of a new
shell.  The user can proceed to use this shell normally, just like the original
shell, save perhaps that the shell inside
.B @PACKAGE@
will not by default be a login shell.  Upon exit, the user will be
returned to the original shell.
.PP
The difference from simply running a new shell is that if the user's
connection to the host is broken (that is, if the
.B @PACKAGE@
client is killed, for instance by
.BR SIGHUP ), 
the shell will not be killed.  It will remain alive in a detached state.
Whatever may have been running inside that
shell can also continue running, and its output will be buffered.
Then if the user logs back in and runs
.B @PACKAGE@
again, instead of starting a new shell,
.B @PACKAGE@
will reconnect to the detached shell.
.SS In more detail,
.PP
.B @PACKAGE@
has a straightforward client-server architecture.  Users interact with
clients, which connect to servers, which contain shells.  In normal
operation, the client and server are invisible and the user has
the same experience as if using the shell directly.
.PP
Upon invocation, the
.B @PACKAGE@
command-line program typically does, or attempts, four things.  This
sequence of steps can be modified by command-line options.
.IP 1. 4
It attempts to verify that it is not running inside an existing
.B @PACKAGE@
session; nesting sessions is usually undesirable.
.IP 2. 4
It searches for a detached
.B @PACKAGE@
server: one started by the current user 
and not currently in use by some other client.
.IP 3. 4
If no usable server was found, it starts a new server, containing a new
shell.
.IP 4. 4
It starts a new client, connected to the server it found or started.
.PP
The client forwards subsequent keystrokes transparently through the server to
the shell, and returns the shell's output back to the user.  Terminal window
size changes also pass through the client-server connection to the shell.
.PP
If and when the shell exits, the server exits.  If and when the server exits,
the client exits.  In normal operation, when the user exits the shell, the
server and client will exit accordingly.  But if the client dies other than
at the behest of the server, then the server and shell continue to
run in a detached state.  Output from the shell is buffered in the server
while detached.  When the user runs
.B @PACKAGE@
again, it will find and re-connect to the detached server.  The buffered
output will then be dumped to the user's new terminal connection, and the
user can continue using the shell.
.SS Which shell?
.PP
When starting a new server with a shell inside it,
.B @PACKAGE@
will by default use the value of the
.B SHELL
environment variable, and will simply execute that path with no command-line
arguments of its own, with the effect that the shell will
.I not
start as a login shell.  The
.I .profile
and similar login-related scripts will not run, and on a typical Linux
installation, things like
.I ls
colours will not work.
.PP
The
.B \-l
or
.B \-\-login-shell
options select a login shell instead.  Running
.B @PACKAGE@
with a single hyphen as a command-line argument, as in
.BR "@PACKAGE@ \-" ,
will do the same.  The request to the shell that it should be a login shell
is communicated by passing it an
.I argv[0]
value beginning with
.BR \- .
.PP
Non-option arguments other than
.B \-
will be taken as the name of the shell to run followed by arguments to give
to it; and as usual,
.B \-\-
signals the end of options for
.BR @PACKAGE@ ,
allowing the specification of arguments for the shell that otherwise would
look like
.B @PACKAGE@
options.  For example,
.B "@PACKAGE@ \-\- /bin/foosh \-bar"
runs the shell
.B /bin/foosh
with the argument
.BR \-bar,
without generating a complaint from
.B @PACKAGE@
that
.B \-bar
is not a valid
.B @PACKAGE@
option argument.
.PP
In the unlikely event that there is no
.B SHELL
environment variable defined,
.B @PACKAGE@
will fall back on the hardcoded path \*(lq/bin/sh\*(rq.
.SS Buffering
.PP
There are some complexities to the handling of buffered output.
Communication between the client and server passes through \*(lqnamed
pipes,\*(rq which include buffers of their own.  On at least some Linux
installations, the named-pipe buffers can hold 64K, but this may vary
depending on the operating system, version, and local configuration.
The buffer in the
.B @PACKAGE@
server will not start to fill until the pipe buffer is full.
Then the server's buffer may also have a limited capacity (approximately 1M
by default, possibly adjustable by means of command line options).
If that fills too, while the server is detached and the software inside the
server is continuing to generate output, then (again, in the default
configuration) the server will start discarding data at the head of its
buffer.
So a user who reconnects after a long absence during which some output
was discarded might typically be
presented with the first 64K of output they missed, followed by the last 1M
of output, with a gap in between.  In the motivating case of a detached program
that is running more or less autonomously and writing an infinte scroll of
\*(lqlog\*(rq information to the terminal, this behaviour is what's desired:
it allows the user to read a decent amount of scrollback, without allowing the
server's memory requirements to grow in an unlimited way nor requiring the
underlying software to stop and wait for the user to reconnect.
.PP
If the client died in a reasonably graceful way, and a new client rejoins
the detached server before the buffers fill, then there should be no data
lost at all.  Really guaranteeing that may not be possible in an ungraceful
situation of network or power loss, however.  And even if no bytes are lost,
software that depends on terminal features to partially repaint the screen
(as with
.IR ncurses )
may end up producing a corrupted display after an interruption.  In many
such packages, it is possible to request a full screen redraw by pressing
.I ^R
or
.IR ^L .
.SS Nesting and multiple sessions
.PP
It is perfectly possible for the same user to have multiple
.B @PACKAGE@
clients and servers active at the same time, but in the event there is more
than one detached server, the order in which new invocations of
.B @PACKAGE@
will pick them up is unspecified by default.
.PP
By default
.B @PACKAGE@
checks whether it is being run inside an existing
.B @PACKAGE@
session and will refuse to create a nested session.  That check is
especially important because in normal operation, a user who types
.B @PACKAGE@
at a shell prompt may just see another shell prompt immediately, not
realize that anything has actually happened, and be inclined to try again.
However,
the
.B \-N
option will override this check and allow creation of nested sessions
to arbitrary depth.  It is even possible to create a looped session
by starting a new client with
.B \-N
inside a server that is already detached; if no other detached servers exist
at the time, the new client will connect to the server that contains itself.
If somehow some output is also introduced into the loop, then the client and
server will soak up CPU time passing the data around as fast as possible,
indefinitely.
Resolving such a situation requires manually killing one of the processes
involved.
.SS Name
.PP
The name of this package refers to the character of John Alden in
.I The Courtship of Miles Standish
by Henry Wadsworth Longfellow.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI "\-B " "N\fR,\fP " "\-\-buffer-size " N
Set the size of each buffer to
.I N
bytes.  Default is 32768, and it is rarely useful to change this.
.TP
.BI "\-D " "N\fR,\fP " "\-\-down-buffers " N
Allow up to
.I N
buffers on the server in the downward (user to shell) direction.  Default is
32, which with the default buffer size means about 1M of data can be
buffered at a time.  Set negative to allow unlimited buffering; otherwise,
when the buffer is full in the downward direction, the server will stop
accepting data, forcing other parts of the system to buffer if they can.
.TP
.BR \-N ", " \-\-allow-nesting
Disable the initial check for whether
.B @PACKAGE@
is running inside an existing session, thus allowing the creation of nested
sessions.
.TP
.BI "\-R " "N\fR,\fP " "\-\-read-size " N
Set the number of bytes to read (in either direction) on each attempt,
default 4096.  Larger numbers may be faster when handling a lot
of data, but because a new buffer is started whenever the server cannot
guarantee the entire read will fit in an existing buffer, smaller numbers
will result in more effective use of memory.
.TP
.BI "\-U " "N\fR,\fP " "\-\-up-buffers " N
Allow up to
.I N
buffers on the server in the upward (shell to user) direction.  Default is
32, which with the default buffer size means about 1M of data can be
buffered at a time.  Set negative to allow unlimited buffering (which can be
dangerous!); otherwise, when the buffer is full in the upward direction, the server will start
throwing away the oldest buffered data, resulting in a skip when the client
reconnects or starts reading again.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Display a brief message identifying the version and license terms of the
software.  Using
.B \-V
or
.B \-h
causes the program to exit after displaying the associated message(s),
without doing anything else.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display a list of available command line options.  Using
.B \-V
or
.B \-h
causes the program to exit after displaying the associated message(s),
without doing anything else.
.TP
.BI "\-i " "N\fR,\fP " "\-\-pid " N
Connect to a server with process ID
.IR N .
This option works by overriding the usual search to only look at the
specified process ID, and it automatically has the effect of setting
.BR \-\-reconnect .
.TP
.BR \-l ", " \-\-login-shell ", " \-
When starting a server (and only if starting a server), run the shell as a
login shell.
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-new-server ", " \-\-no-search
Disable the search for an existing server; then (unless this other step
is also disabled) the program will necessarily start a new server.
.TP
.BR \-r ", " \-\-reconnect
Disable starting a new server; then the program must reconnect to an existing
detached server, or fail.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-server-only
Disable starting a client; the server (if one is started) will remain
detached, ready for later connections.  This option has the effect of setting
.BR \-\-no-search ,
because there is no use finding an existing server if we won't connect to
it.  The PID of the server that was started, will be written to standard
out.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Report detailed progress messages to standard error.
.TP
.B \-\-list
Find all available servers and write their PIDs to standard out, then exit
without doing other steps.
Servers with currently-attached clients are not listed.
.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.IP SHELL
This is the shell that will be started inside a newly-started
.B @PACKAGE@
server.
.
